      "why_it_matters": "Affects how we test loadSession/saveSession interactions and whether corrupt storage tests need manual prototype manipulation or simple mock returns."
    },
    {
      "id": "q2",
      "question": "Should the test file use renderWithProviders from helpers.tsx (which wraps SessionProvider along with QueryClient and MemoryRouter), or render SessionProvider directly for isolated context testing?",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "renderWithProviders already wraps SessionProvider, so using it for useSession tests would add unnecessary providers. Direct rendering gives cleaner isolation but deviates from the project's established pattern."
    },
    {
      "id": "q3",
      "question": "For the 'useSession error outside provider' test, should we suppress the expected React error boundary console.error output to keep test output clean?",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "React logs errors to console when rendering fails. Without suppression, passing tests produce noisy error output that could confuse developers reading test results."
    },
    {
      "id": "q4",
      "question": "The isConfigured flag only checks accountId.length > 0 and ignores agentId. Should the tests explicitly verify this behavior (agentId alone does NOT make isConfigured true)?",
